FOUNDRY IAM

CUSTOM FEDERATION &

BRING YOUR OWN IdP

Feature Specification — Phase 2





Document Type

Feature Extension Spec

Phase

Phase 2 — Post-MVP

Estimated Build

7–10 engineering days

Trigger

Enterprise requiring SSO via existing Okta / Azure AD / Google

Revenue Impact

Required for enterprise SLA. Often the primary SSO requirement.

Dependencies

MVP platform live. SAML spec optional (SAML upstream requires SAML spec).



This document specifies the Custom Federation and Bring Your Own IdP (BYO IdP) feature. It enables enterprise customers to connect their existing corporate Identity Provider (Okta, Azure AD / Entra ID, Google Workspace, or any OIDC/SAML upstream) to their Foundry IAM workspace, so their employees log in using company credentials rather than Foundry IAM-native accounts. An engineer receiving only this document should be able to implement this feature without access to other platform documentation.



SECTION 1

Concept — What Custom Federation Is





1.1 The Problem It Solves

Without federation, every user who needs access to a customer's application must be manually created in Foundry IAM (or via SCIM). For an enterprise with existing Okta or Azure AD, this creates a parallel identity store — users have two sets of credentials, two places to be deprovisioned, and two authentication experiences.



With Custom Federation (BYO IdP), the customer connects their existing corporate IdP to their Foundry IAM workspace. Their employees then click 'Sign in with Acme Corp' on the Keycloak login page, are redirected to Okta/Azure AD for authentication, and returned to Keycloak with a trusted assertion. Keycloak creates a federated user record and issues its own OIDC tokens downstream. The customer's application never sees the upstream IdP — only Foundry IAM tokens.



1.2 The Authentication Flow

Without BYO IdP:

  User → Keycloak login page → enter Foundry IAM password → JWT



With BYO IdP (OIDC upstream — e.g. Google, Okta):

  User → Keycloak login page → click 'Sign in with Acme Corp'

    → Redirect to Okta (customer's IdP)

      → User authenticates with Okta (existing credentials, MFA, etc.)

        → Okta returns OIDC token to Keycloak

          → Keycloak creates/updates federated user in realm

            → Keycloak issues Foundry IAM JWT to customer application



With BYO IdP (SAML upstream — e.g. Azure AD):

  User → Keycloak login page → click 'Sign in with Acme Corp'

    → Redirect to Azure AD (SAML AuthnRequest)

      → User authenticates with Azure AD

        → Azure AD returns SAML Assertion to Keycloak (Keycloak acts as SAML SP)

          → Keycloak creates/updates federated user

            → Keycloak issues Foundry IAM JWT to customer application



1.3 Supported Upstream IdP Types

Type

Protocol

Examples

Keycloak Support

Social / Pre-built

OIDC

Google, GitHub, Microsoft (personal), Facebook

Built-in. Social provider config in Keycloak Admin.

OIDC Enterprise

OIDC / OpenID Connect

Okta, Auth0, Ping Identity, any OIDC-compliant IdP

Keycloak Identity Broker — generic OIDC.

SAML Enterprise

SAML 2.0

Azure AD / Entra ID, Active Directory FS, Shibboleth, any SAML 2.0 IdP

Keycloak Identity Broker — generic SAML.

LDAP / Active Directory

LDAP

On-premise Active Directory, OpenLDAP

Keycloak LDAP federation — different config, covered in Section 7.



1.4 Keycloak's Role — Identity Brokering

Keycloak's Identity Broker capability handles the upstream federation natively. Foundry IAM's work is building the management layer: the API to configure brokers, the portal UI for customers to add their IdP, and the control plane logic to store and manage configurations.



Key Concept: Broker vs. Direct Federation

Foundry IAM does NOT pass through authentication to the upstream IdP. Keycloak brokers the identity: it authenticates against the upstream, then issues its own JWT downstream. Customer applications always receive Foundry IAM tokens — they never need to know about the upstream IdP. This is the correct architecture and it is what makes the product vendor-neutral.





SECTION 2

Architecture — No New Services Required





Custom federation requires no new services. Keycloak's Identity Broker is already in the platform. The work is: control plane API endpoints to manage broker configurations, portal UI pages for customers to configure their IdP, and the database tables to persist configurations outside of Keycloak.



2.1 Identity Broker Configuration Flow

Customer (portal admin):

  Navigates to Workspace → Identity Providers → Add Provider

  Selects: Google / Okta (OIDC) / Azure AD (SAML) / Custom OIDC / Custom SAML

  Fills in required fields (varies by type — see Section 4)

  Clicks 'Save and Test'

    ↓

Control Plane API:

  POST /v1/workspaces/:id/identity-providers

  Validates fields

  Calls Keycloak Admin API to create Identity Provider in realm

  Applies mappers (attribute mapping from upstream to Keycloak user profile)

  Persists configuration to identity_providers table

  Returns configuration + test URL

    ↓

Customer tests the flow:

  Opens test URL in browser

  Redirected to their IdP → authenticates → returns to Keycloak

  Keycloak shows 'Link to existing account?' or creates federated user

    ↓

Configuration is live.

Login page for this realm now shows the IdP button.



2.2 How Federated Users Work in Keycloak

Behaviour

Details

First login

Keycloak creates a user record in the realm with the federated identity linked. Username is typically the upstream email or sub claim.

Subsequent logins

Keycloak recognises the federated identity link. No duplicate user created. Claims are refreshed from upstream.

Local account linking

If a user already has a Foundry IAM local account with the same email, Keycloak prompts to link the accounts. Configurable policy.

User attributes

Attribute mappers copy claims from the upstream token (email, name, groups) into Keycloak user profile. These appear in Foundry IAM JWTs.

User management

Federated users appear in the Keycloak users list. Their source is marked as the IdP alias. They can be manually disabled.

Deprovisioning

Foundry IAM does not auto-deprovision federated users when they leave the upstream IdP. SCIM (separate feature) handles automated deprovisioning.





