6.2 Add Identity Provider Flow (IdPNew.tsx) — UX Spec

The provider selection step is critical UX. Show tiles/cards, not a dropdown. Visual recognition of logos (Okta, Azure AD, Google, GitHub) dramatically reduces configuration errors and support tickets.



Step 1 — Provider Selection: Show provider tiles with logos and labels: 'Okta', 'Azure AD', 'Google Workspace', 'GitHub', 'Generic OIDC', 'Generic SAML'. Single click to proceed.

Step 2 — Configuration Form: Fields vary by provider type. For known providers (Okta, Google), show only the minimum required fields and auto-populate known URLs. For Generic OIDC/SAML, show all fields.

Step 3 — Callback URL Display: Before saving, show the callback URL the customer must register in their upstream IdP. Show a 'I have registered this URL in my IdP' checkbox. Warn clearly that if this step is skipped, the integration will fail.

Step 4 — Attribute Mapper Defaults: Apply default mappers for the provider type (email, firstName, lastName). Show them as editable. Add mapper button for custom claims.

Step 5 — Save and Test: Save button provisions the IdP. On success, show 'Test this configuration' button that opens the test URL in a new tab.



6.3 Provider-Specific Form Fields

Provider

Required Fields (auto-populated where possible)

Notes

Google Workspace

Client ID, Client Secret, Hosted Domain (restrict to company email)

Consent screen setup in Google Cloud Console. Callback URL to add: shown in Step 3.

GitHub

Client ID, Client Secret, Organization (optional — restrict to org members)

OAuth App in GitHub Settings. Callback URL required.

Okta

Okta Domain (e.g. acme.okta.com), Client ID, Client Secret — all other URLs auto-derived from domain

System apps → Create App Integration → OIDC → Web App. Add callback URL.

Azure AD / SAML

Tenant ID (auto-derives SAML URLs), Signing Certificate, NameID format

Azure Portal → Enterprise Applications → New → Non-gallery → SAML. Use SP metadata URL.

Generic OIDC

Authorization URL, Token URL, UserInfo URL, JWKS URL, Client ID, Client Secret, Scopes

Full manual config. Point to upstream .well-known/openid-configuration for URL hints.

Generic SAML

SSO URL, SLO URL (optional), IdP Entity ID, Signing Certificate

Upload IdP metadata XML to auto-populate, or enter manually.



6.4 IdP Detail Page — UX Spec

Header: Provider logo + display name + alias + status badge (Active/Disabled). Enable/Disable toggle.

Callback URLs section: Prominently displayed. Copy button. Provider-specific instructions (e.g. 'Add this as a redirect URI in your Okta App Settings').

Test section: 'Test authentication' button. Opens test URL in new browser tab. On return, show last test result timestamp and success/error.

Configuration section: Redacted config display (client_secret shown as *** with 'Update' button). All non-secret fields editable inline.

Attribute Mappers section: Table of upstream claim → Foundry IAM user attribute mappings. Add/edit/delete rows. Save button.

Domain Routing section: List of email domains (e.g. acme.com). Users with matching email domain automatically redirected to this IdP at login. Add/remove domains.

Danger zone: Delete IdP. Warns that federated users will lose SSO and may be unable to login. Requires typing IdP alias to confirm.



SECTION 7

LDAP / Active Directory Federation





Scope Note

LDAP federation is architecturally different from OIDC/SAML brokering. It requires network connectivity from Keycloak to the customer's LDAP server, which is complex in a hosted SaaS context. This section specifies LDAP support but marks it as a gated feature (Enterprise plan only) due to the operational complexity.



7.1 What LDAP Federation Provides

Users in the customer's on-premise Active Directory or OpenLDAP can authenticate against Foundry IAM without being migrated

Keycloak reads user attributes directly from LDAP on login

Group membership in LDAP can be synchronised to Keycloak groups

Passwords are validated against LDAP — Foundry IAM never stores the LDAP password



7.2 Network Requirement — Why This Is Gated

Keycloak must be able to establish a TCP connection to the customer's LDAP server (typically port 389 for LDAP or 636 for LDAPS). In a hosted SaaS, this means the customer must either:



Option A: Expose their LDAP/LDAPS server publicly with IP allowlist (Foundry IAM egress IP). High security risk — strongly discourage.

Option B: VPN or private link between Foundry IAM infrastructure and customer network. Operationally complex, customer-specific engineering.

Option C: Customer deploys Keycloak on their own infrastructure (BYOK — Bring Your Own Keycloak). Not applicable to the hosted SaaS.

Option D: Customer migrates to cloud-hosted LDAP (Azure AD DS, AWS Directory Service). Then LDAPS is reachable via LDAPS URL.



Recommendation

For Phase 2, LDAP is documented but not actively sold. When a customer requests it, assess which option is feasible for their environment and flag as a custom implementation engagement. LDAP over public internet without VPN should be refused on security grounds.



7.3 LDAP Configuration Table (for future implementation)

